node.text: We picked two avocados the other day from one of our trees and it was divine. There is really nothing like a fresh avocado. The Bahamian variety here are really deep yellow,  so savoury, and just perfect. Every time I cut one open I think of our girl Pumps. As you all know they were her favourite. During lockdown I wrote a little essay about the time I decided to be wild and make a sweet avocado tart (yes it can be done) and it was divine. I wasn’t sure what I wanted to do with this essay, I had so many projects in mind but I recruited the incredibly talented @clairefletcherillustration to create some images of our girl. Pumpkin the chef? Sure why not! Maybe one day I’ll share the essay and recipe, but for now here is just a lovely memory of our girl. ❤️

node.text: I made pancakes today for my older little madam this morning after an incredibly shocking few days. A summer school bug took down our family in a very dramatic way (not covid) and it’s been almost five days of zero sleep with a baby that has literally never been sick. It’s been a doozy. I slept last night from 9.30pm until 5.30am and feel like a completely new woman! The babes were still asleep, husband still asleep, animals still asleep. It was pretty perfect. I made myself tea, went outside and enjoyed the sunrise, then I made nutritious pancakes because let’s be honest, no one had been eating well these past five days it was survival mode for us. While making the pancakes I started remembering Pumps and all the things she loved to eat, including pancakes doused in maple syrup. This was never actually something we gave her but she would steal one or two from us in her classic stealth mode. Her love of food was something very entertaining and were always the photos most of you enjoyed the best. As I type this I’m smiling, and even though chaos is now starting, baby is up, I’m arguing with the four year old about eating her breakfast, snotty husband sneezing constantly, I’ll take it. Because mama slept!

So hopefully I’ll see you there for a drink… or two! Peace and love, Team Pumps Xoxox

node.text: Saying Goodbye (Pt 4) When the call from the vet came I was ready. “The mass was too big Laura. I am so sorry but the right thing to do is to let her go.” I quietly agreed and slumped into Will. “She’s gone”, I whispered and we hugged and cried. I felt so lost and just didn’t know what to do with myself. When I have tried to explain the pain of losing Pumpkin, some people understand and some people don’t. She really was more than just my pet. After she was gone I realised how she had impacted my life and helped shape me. I have always had animals in my life but I have never felt the loss of an animal the way I felt hers. I cried every morning when I woke up for what seemed like weeks. I couldn’t mention her name without welling up. So many of you since I shared about her passing have written the most beautiful messages to me saying how much she had impacted your lives and brought joy. She did the same for me. She became my little muse and inspired me in ways I didn’t know possible. She ignited my creative side which I had suppressed for so long and dared me to believe that maybe, just maybe I could start believing in myself and give my dreams a chance. Those first few hours after we said goodbye to her were daggers to my heart, but now I am able to glance up at that empty cupboard space and smile and remember her fondly. I can now picture the book I want to write about her, and I can think of all the other little stories I want to share. I also just want to say thank you. Thank you to you all for sticking with me and for being such incredible support through all of this. You are the most incredible group of people and I wish you all could have met her. You made this horrible time easier and I will never forget it. So as I write this with tears pouring down my face, as always, peace and Love Team Pumps xox

node.text: The morning of the surgery was such a blur I made sure she was as comfortable as possible. We gave her so much love. We kept her calm and happy in her favourite spot in the cupboard. When it was time for me to get her down I cried so deeply. I cried into the fur on her little head and when I moved away she licked my tears like she had done on so many occasions with me. She was so gentle and so calm, she was letting me know it was okay. I remember begging the vet to fix her, I asked if she would be okay. “I will do my best, and everything I can to make sure she can go home”. I knew though. I was so desperate to believe she would be okay. We were taken to a small room where they gave her another sedative to help keep her calm before they prepped her for surgery. In that little sterile room is where my husband and I both cried and cried and said our goodbye. We both didn’t want it to be that way, but we both felt the reality deep down. In that twenty minutes before I took her in I hugged her, and told her how much I loved her, how much she had meant to me. She wasn’t just a pet, she was so much more. It is said over and over again that animals come into your life for different reasons and I knew why she entered mine. She saved me from deep dark depression, my anxieties, she literally fell into our lives when I needed her the most. She gave me a purpose, bottle feeding her every two hours, to calling her inside at night like a grumpy teenager when she got older. She was always by my side when I would cry from panic and fear surrounding my pregnancy and let me know I was going to be okay when I didn’t think I would be. She was there when my first daughter was born and she was by my side as I tried to navigate the crazy journey of motherhood. In those twenty minutes I got to thank her. I had my chance to tell her she was loved and I would never forget her, because how many people get a chance to rescue and raise a crazy chubby raccoon? When it was time to take her in for surgery I kissed her sleepy little body and whispered that if she needed to go it was okay, I would be okay. I asked the vets to do their best and left with tears streaming down my swollen red face.

node.text: Saying Goodbye (Pt 2) Up until that point Pumpkin had been completely her normal self. There was nothing off about it. I went and picked up our girl all groggy and sleepy and brought her home to rest, and I knew. I knew in my bones something wasn’t right. We spent that evening babying her and cuddling her and making sure she was as comfortable as possible. She was still so out of it from being sedated but she would nuzzle me and just plop beside me wanting to be warm and loved. The next morning I got the call. The x-ray that they had initially thought was a clear picture of her stomach wasn’t in fact her stomach. It was a giant mass. And it didn’t take long for me to understand the tone in her voice that the situation wasn't good. I asked all the questions about what the best option was. What could we do? There were only two, either trying to perform a surgery to remove the mass, or end her pain by doing the humane thing of putting her to sleep. I hung up the phone and began sobbing my eyes out. What should I do? The surgery my vet advised maynot be successful and she may not recover well from it. She will be in pain and will have to be sedated for a long time in order for her to heal, and even then it may not be enough. Will and I spoke about it for what seemed like hours but in reality the decision had to be made so quickly. Pumpkin was suffering, she was in pain. We would try for the surgery. We needed to try.
